<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-383-778  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 383 778.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 23 1990 n587 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Where are the business-savvy engineers? (Speakout)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mayhew, Lawrence.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>American engineering schools excel in developing the world'sfinest technical minds.andP;  Emphasis is placed on intensive study,with a critical focus on the personal and technological challengesof producing state-of-the-art products.andP;  A critical flaw in thistraining, however, is the lack of any attempt to acquaintengineering students with the real-world constraints ofproduction.andP;  This not only creates problems for line engineers whomust produce viable products; it can have an even more devastatingimpact when engineers are promoted to management positions wherethey must make business decisions with no previous training orexperience to fall back on.andP;  The solution to the problem istwo-fold: engineering schools must add to their curricula therealities of commercial engineering, and industry must become moreinvolved in the training of engineers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EngineeringTrainingBusiness EducationGuidelinesManagement Science.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>